commit_message:
Fix broken master repo

Because of the new gating system (gate-training-guides-tox-slides), we need to
cleanup all existing RST files.

There is a small rendering problem with Landslide in the Upstream training
and all the Title slides (empty slides with only a Title). The check doesn't
like "empty" slides ("Document or section may not begin with a transition."),
Landslide deals with this by ignoring errors
(https://github.com/adamzap/landslide/issues/94), but our gating check does
not. I temporary changed all such slides to normal ones.

I also had to change training-guides/landslide.sh a bit (a quick hack so that
it works as expected).

Change-Id: I6c3ae06235e69c4a53741e74a5642d27083f4df0

commit_message:
Failover to alternative iSCSI portals on login failure

Some Cinder iSCSI backend drivers may return alternative
portals/tragets/luns information in the response from
initialize_connection API, for the case the main portal
is unreachable by network failure. This patch enables
brick to fail-over to alternative portals when it fails
to establish a session to the main portal.

Change-Id: Ic08d018d3b5f282ece823971576043f76bad1b2d
Implements: blueprint iscsi-alternative-portal

commit_message:
Refactor RootHelperProcess with AsyncProcess

* RootHelperProcess and AsyncProcess have duplicate functions so we merge
all functions of RootHelperProcess in functional test to AsyncProcess
in common lib.
* Add optional param 'wait_cmd_start' for AsyncProcess to wait for the
command of the child process to start executing before it can return to
main process. This solves concurrent call in the main process, which
depends on the start of the child process. Defaults to False.
* Add optional param 'read_std_to_queue' to enable/disable reading result
into a queue. Defaults to True.
* Refactor NetcatTester in functional test to use AsyncProcess instead
of RootHelperProcess.

commit_message:
Revert "Overhaul bash-completion to support non-UUID based IDs"

This reverts commit 4c8cefb98a425382204df2f38f24e6b5b71520dd.

The cache completion was causing a bug where 'nova volume-attach' would
then try to query Nova for volume information using a URL that was not
valid.  This caused it to appear that the attach had failed.

Additionally the idea of making extra API queries for a bash completion
cache should be thought through more.

Conflicts:

	novaclient/client.py
	novaclient/shell.py
	novaclient/v2/client.py
	novaclient/v3/client.py

Closes-Bug: #1423695
Change-Id: I6676a11f9b5318a1cda2d03a5d4550bda549d5c2

commit_message:
Reduce the set of supported client SSL ciphers

python-glanceclient (like, for example, curl) can advertise the default
set of supported OpenSSL ciphers in its ClientHello packet.

This patches reduces that to a stronger subset.

Change-Id: I7c30465e79d8a32f43458cd6253a98fcf067dc38
Closes-bug: #1370283

commit_message:
Wrap IPv6 address in square brackets for scp/rsync

Address, contained in nova.netconf.my_ip config option, is passed to
scp/rsync when copying image during migration.  If this option contains
IPv6 address, scp/rsync fails.

Wrapping IPv6 address in square brackets solves this problem.  Code was
adopted from swift project.

Change-Id: Ia5f28673e79158d948980f2b3ce496c6a56882af
Closes-Bug: #1422691

commit_message:
Using eventlet monkey patch an all recommended module

eventlet by default monkey patch all supported/safe
modules to be preemptive in order to avoiding deadlocks and
improve the performance.

Change-Id: Ia82ae8bc7a795fa3175613b449b77013f5888324

commit_message:
Revert "Add ceph object storage meters"

The ceilometer-acentral is not able start in the gate jobs,
because the reverted commit uses the requests-aws unconditionally.

The rgw plugin should be optional and it's usage needs to be
configureable.

This reverts commit 9518c8f0c75673ea5ada7ab34af5325cbd0dabd1.

commit_message:
Don't compare images when image is None

Image cache can set images to None under certain workflow,
and then we are accessing this None entry as it was
an object. Add an extra check for that.

Change-Id: Ia9b737c81ed8133ff5a6ba26f98b7f55fca095de

commit_message:
Change os-ansible-deployment checks to use scripts

This commit changes the os-ansible-deployment checks to exclusively
make use of scripts which are located in the repository which is
cloned. This is done to improve flexibility - if the check needs to
change, it can be done within the script instead of submitting a review
to the project-config.

This commit also implements the commit check as a voting check across
all branches, and also changes the merge check from the lint check to
the commit check.

Change-Id: I95d4f12e374b80be70f513429a5dc04b0bdf3534

commit_message:
Update apt cache after adding repos or pinning

This patch implements a forced apt cache update after a new apt
repository is added, or any apt pinning is implemented.

This ensures that apt is sure about what packages are available to it,
and which packages/repositories should be preferred above others.

Change-Id: I2f6e9fa33c7765e8ed8aeaf4ea60be696125c186
Closes-Bug: #1421679

the lib/puppet/provider/nova_network/nova_manage.rb provider was using

commit_message:
--vlan is not the same as --vlan_start

the lib/puppet/provider/nova_network/nova_manage.rb provider was using
the --vlan option when it meant --vlan_start.  This caused "network
create" commands with num_networks > 1 to fail with "duplicate vlan"
errors.

Change-Id: Ibdca3b8de72b459eacf8b44b6350b9bc71310c1b
Closes-bug: #1362772
(cherry picked from commit c40e67f1b5cd59a1755d451e00578404fd5d4c61)

commit_message:
Allow upload_file with empty data

There are cases when we would like to upload a file but with data
considered by Ruby as "blank": whitespaces, empty file, etc.
This change allows to upload an empty file - now only presence of
'data' param in upload_file will be checked, not content.

Change-Id: I0b48ffd8e291836e1e5b6d63676aad8981de2d5c
Partial-Bug: #1422341

is a wrong place for expressing Debian packages' dependencies.

commit_message:
ceph: don't to install python-pushy on Ubuntu

First of all ceph-deploy 1.5.x (the current version packaged for Ubuntu)
does not use pushy at all. Secondly (and most importantly) puppet manifests
is a wrong place for expressing Debian packages' dependencies.

blueprint support-ubuntu-trusty
Closes-Bug: #1419774

Change-Id: I3b938aa38bde3d71ba1c690de8d6406c5c331088

revisions:
[{'number': 6, 'created': '2015-02-20 12:13:31.000000000', 'files': ['deployment/puppet/keystone/files/httpd/keystone.py', 'deployment/puppet/zabbix/files/scripts/check_api.py', '.gitignore', 'deployment/puppet/nova/files/connection.py', 'deployment/puppet/cobbler/templates/scripts/late_command.py', 'deployment/puppet/osnailyfacter/modular/astute/vcenter_compute_zones.py', 'deployment/puppet/cluster/files/q-agent-cleanup.py', 'utils/jenkins/python_run_tests.sh', 'deployment/puppet/openstack/files/filter_quantum_ports.py', 'utils/jenkins/tox.ini', 'utils/jenkins/python-test-requirements.txt', 'deployment/puppet/zabbix/files/scripts/query_db.py', 'deployment/puppet/cobbler/templates/scripts/pmanager.py', 'deployment/puppet/cobbler/examples/cobbler_system.py', 'deployment/puppet/zabbix/files/scripts/check_rabbit.py'], 'message': "Add way to run Python tests

Added script to easily run Python tests in fuel-library.
Script is located in ./utils/jenkins/python_run_tests.sh and
uses tox to create environments and py.test as a test runner.

Usage of the script can be learn from running it with '-h' arg:
 ./python_run_tests.sh -h

commit_message:
Add way to run Python tests

Added script to easily run Python tests in fuel-library.
Script is located in ./utils/jenkins/python_run_tests.sh and
uses tox to create environments and py.test as a test runner.

Usage of the script can be learn from running it with '-h' arg:
 ./python_run_tests.sh -h

Tests include running all found Python tests as well
'flake8' with 'hacking' checks in newest version.

Requirements for tests could be found in
./utils/jenkins/python-test-requirements.txt

tox.ini. is located in
./utils/jenkins/tox.ini

Disabled all flake8 checks in all currently failing files.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I283333c48ac53d7baa0a9bb04558d7317bdcec11

commit_message:
CinderException args to strings when exceptions

CinderException message and kwargs are converted to strings if the
argument is itself an exception.

Exceptions passed as arguments to CinderException happen in many areas
of the code. This causes an error when oslo.messaging tries to serialise
the exception.

Change-Id: I1399c939bbca47ab8362ac3bbe0e9a349c6d5572
Closes-Bug: #1301249
(cherry picked from commit 31a09451394458273ae1ed9af867476da4ece9d6)

commit_message:
boot instance with same net-id for multiple --nic

'allow_duplicate_networks' flag should allow an instance to have
multiple vNICs attached to the same Neutron network.

After setting this flag to true, booting instance with multiple
interfaces to attach to same network(with same net-id) like below
is failing.

nova boot --flavor m1.small --image rhel7-new
--nic net-id=52fc18b6-397a-45d6-b8db-fb32accd00e5
--nic net-id=52fc18b6-397a-45d6-b8db-fb32accd00e5 vm100

We have check for duplicate networks at nova api layer(i.e nova/api/
openstack/compute/servers.py). We can just skip this check when we are
using neutron. Because we already have same check in network api(i.e
nova/network/neutronv2/api.py) and also as 'allow_duplicate_networks'
flag is only for nova neutron.

Closes-Bug: #1400037
Change-Id: I7ee4e03a8fda3796606fb4618b95999b7580561d
(cherry picked from commit cd6c48abd592e3a40153c555ee2aa91ac773c820)

subject: Ironic: Bump memory size for non-concurrency job
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2015-02-18 17:37:26.000000000', 'files': ['devstack-vm-gate.sh'], 'message': "Ironic: Bump memory size for non-concurrency job

In Ironic we want to be able to use the IPA ramdisk as the default ramdisk
for our deployments, since that ramdisk is a heavier than our previous one
we need to bump the memory size from 512MB to 1GB to be able to test it
in gate. It's important to note that since the cuncurrency job needs 3 VMs
we will still run it using the old ramdisk until we can solve the problem.

Plus, for normal jobs where we bumped the RAM size we are lowering the
number of VMs created from 3 to 1, because only 1 VM get's used anyway.

Change-Id: Ic06e4ab76398ff90d6635b159beb8c06dc907da0
"}]
commit_message:
Ironic: Bump memory size for non-concurrency job

In Ironic we want to be able to use the IPA ramdisk as the default ramdisk
for our deployments, since that ramdisk is a heavier than our previous one
we need to bump the memory size from 512MB to 1GB to be able to test it
in gate. It's important to note that since the cuncurrency job needs 3 VMs
we will still run it using the old ramdisk until we can solve the problem.

Plus, for normal jobs where we bumped the RAM size we are lowering the
number of VMs created from 3 to 1, because only 1 VM get's used anyway.

Change-Id: Ic06e4ab76398ff90d6635b159beb8c06dc907da0

commit_message:
Override cinder-volume service only for Cinder role

W/o this fix, tweaks::ubuntu_service_override { 'cinder-volume' }
is called for controller and compute roles as well as for cinder role
and that causes the double declaration conflict.
The solution is to invoke this override only for cinder role.

Change-Id: I3b49968bb1c38d55cece507e0e7f5b950f890c1f
Closes-bug: #1422579
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Add sanity_check for keepalived

Currently Neutron does not validate the version of Keepalived.
In order to support configuring IPv6 default route, the minimum
version [1] of keepalived that is required is 1.2.10
This patch adds a sanity check to validate the keepalived version.

Although keepalived changelog mentions that IPv6 virtual_routes and
static_routes are supported in version 1.2.8, it is seen that in
v1.2.8 IPv6 default route is not supported. Support for default route
is added in keepalived v1.2.10. Observations on v1.2.8 are captured
at the following link - http://paste.openstack.org/show/165403/

[1] - http://www.keepalived.org/changelog.html

Co-Authored-By: Ihar Hrachyshka <ihrachys@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1415756
Change-Id: Ia41e81f98c7fc1797623f352c41e38064b38f447

commit_message:
Add setuptools to global requirements

Some things (namely stevedore) already depend on setuptools
but they rely on the fact that setuptools is often implicitly
available by it's nature of being a commonly installed tool.
However setuptools is not a mandatory library, and pip in
particular can install from Wheels without setuptools being
present. To rectify this setuptools needs added to the
requirements of any project that depends on it at runtime.

Change-Id: Icd83a9aed56942108f240824231216b05b873b3b

commit_message:
Move horizon iptables script to run after os-apply-config init

Prior to configure.d/20-*, os-apply-config cannot be used
to extract individual values from metadata provided via heat.
This patch moves the iptables rule setup for horizon (which
depends on the horizon.port value from Heat) so that it runs
later in the os-refresh-config cycle.

Change-Id: I137ba1acb8d48760162cb750912f640115b91b6b

In Ironic we want to be able to use the IPA ramdisk as the default ramdisk
for our deployments. Since that ramdisk is a heavier than our previous one

in gate. It's important to note that since the concurrency job needs 3 VMs

commit_message:
Ironic: Bump memory size for non-concurrency job

In Ironic we want to be able to use the IPA ramdisk as the default ramdisk
for our deployments. Since that ramdisk is a heavier than our previous one
we need to bump the memory size from 512MB to 1GB to be able to test it
in gate. It's important to note that since the concurrency job needs 3 VMs
we will still run it using the old ramdisk until we can solve the problem.

Plus, for normal jobs where we bumped the RAM size we are lowering the
number of VMs created from 3 to 1, because only 1 VM get's used anyway.

This patch is making use of the new DEVSTACK_LOCAL_CONFIG that allows
passing arbitrary config options to devstack-gate.

Change-Id: I1cd0f34dad0fa2d871671ae745b8ab7eedd4f672

commit_message:
WIP: Ensure a cluster is only ever managed by a single Nova compute

This is a proposed fix for:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1419785

The above happens when you configure 2 HA nodes with different
hostnames to manage the same cluster. On failover, badness ensues when
the incorrectly hostnamed standby tries to take over.

It would be nice to fix the badness, however it is currently very
deeply engrained in Nova. Lots of things assume a consistent 'host',
and they will all be broken in this scenario. Instead, this patch
detects a change of Nova compute, and rejects it.

During the driver's init_host it checks all managed clusters for the
custom value 'openstack_compute_host'. If the value is not present, it
sets it to the current host. If it is, it checks it against the
current hostname. It will raise an Exception if any non-matching
values are found, which in turn will cause Nova to fail to start.

Change-Id: I70ddb491e57b71ddba78cb0cdc39d8d885882d88
Closes-bug: #1419785

commit_message:
Change in default location of log file

The default log file was '/var/log/freezer.log' which
is usually non user writable. That resulted in an exception being
raised when run as a normal user without specifying a writable
location

Now freezer still tries to write to '/var/log/freezer.log',
but falls back to '~/.freezer/freezer.log' in case of error

Errors while opening log file won't print the traceback anymore,
but result in simple error message and coherent exit value.

Change-Id: I17d0421b049f18417f21df81cb48b6fad76829e6
Closes-Bug: #1420842

commit_message:
Restart haproxy in AWS LB during boot

One of possibilities of AWS LoadBalancer usage is to pass it the list of
instance id's to manage already in the template during create.
This patch actually enables this scenario by (re)starting the haproxy
service to catch the created config with initial servers in it.

Note that the other usage scenario (passing the LB id to the *Group
resource) was not affected as in this case there is implicit update of
AWS LB resource that restarts the haproxy service.

Appropriate functional/scenario test is coming in a subsequent patch.

Change-Id: I85a6d67384e2174cba6e1e7e9666b854e11ab5d3

commit_message:
spec: updates for rspec-puppet 2.x and rspec 3.x

This patch aim to update our specs test in order to work with the new
rspec-puppet release 2.0.0, in the mean time, we update rspec syntax
in order to be prepared for rspec 3.x move.

In details:

  * Use shared_examples "a Puppet::Error" for puppet::error tests
  * Convert 'should' keyword to 'is_expected.to' (prepare rspec 3.x)
  * Fix spec tests for rspec-puppet 2.0.0
  * Upgrade and pin rspec-puppet from 1.0.1 to 2.0.0
  * Clean Gemfile (remove over-specificication of runtime deps of puppetlabs_spec_helper)
  * Add parameter documentation checks
  * Fix manifests lint issues, and metadata (spdx license and open deps.)

Card: https://trello.com/c/eHXc1Ryd/4-investigate-the-necessary-change-to-be-rspec-puppet-2-0-0-compliant
Change-Id: I50c23c254302258b6ec62cb4e0c134056067a8e8

commit_message:
Operate on joined graph in nailgun

This patch introduces changes that necesarry to join all stages
into one graph.

<stage>_start is root for stage entity
<stage>_end is end task in stage entity

That is done to ensure that each stage is self contained,
and for example in case of adding more stages there will be no need to
look for end tasks and connect them

The only two harcdoded parameters are deploy_start and deploy_end,
stuff that we are including in pre_deployment is everything that comes before
deploy_start, and for post_deployment after deploy_end

related to blueprint granular-deployment-based-on-tasks

Change-Id: Ida5880525f9c3428ad8bb590f7ef78a0b20b1049

commit_message:
Remove '--id' option from magnum commands.

This patch removes the unnecessary '--id' option
from below magnum commands:

- bay-delete
- bay-show
- baymodel-delete
- baymodel-show
- container-delete
- container-show
- container-execute
- container-logs
- container-pause
- container-reboot
- container-start
- container-stop
- container-unpause
- pod-delete
- pod-show
- rc-delete
- rc-show
- service-delete
- service-show

Now the commands can be run without passing
'--id' option as below:

magnum baymodel-show <id>

Change-Id: I568c43ddb79e700417f0a143a338a7d357ec5f60
Closes-bug: #1410579

commit_message:
Ironic Management Interfaces to support UEFI Secure Boot

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/ironic/+spec/uefi-secure-boot-management-
interfaces

Some of the Ironic deploy drivers support UEFI boot. It would be useful to
security sensitive users to deploy more securely using Secure Boot feature
of the UEFI. This spec proposes Ironic Management APIs that would help in UEFI
Secure Boot deployment of Baremetal.

Change-Id: Iaccd29f684d8361b693683e5d63d12fc3c75431a

commit_message:
Adds an "inline" query parameter to tempurl

Giving the inline query parameter will cause the tempurl
 response to be given a "Content-Disposition: inline" header,
 regardless of other query parameters or metadata.
 This allows easy in-line viewing, for example in browsers.

Change-Id: I62fbcbf1adb690edd314c8efc9b8a04b27670a6d
Closes-Bug: #1254200

commit_message:
Add base rules to enable/disable EC2 new policy

This patch adds rule "disable_ec2_policy" to control whether the
new ec2 policy is enabled or not. Default the value is '@' that means
new ec2 policy is disabled. If operator want to enable the new policy,
operator can set the value to '!'.

The rule "disable_ec2_policy" will be deleted after the old rules is
deprecated totally.

This patch also adds new policy rule in new config file in policy.d.

Partially implements blueprint v3-api-policy
DocImpact

Change-Id: I1877782d39ffb16125276b0078471a44df71b3ce

subject: Make GetOrHeadHandler take an optional chunk size.
revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2015-02-20 20:36:49.000000000', 'files': ['test/unit/proxy/controllers/test_base.py', 'swift/proxy/controllers/base.py'], 'message': "Make GetOrHeadHandler take an optional chunk size.

If given the chunk size, chunks are yielded to the client in exactly
that size (except the last chunk). Data read from the object server
will be buffered until there's a full chunk.

This is good for EC because we can set this to the size of a fragment,
then instantiate a bunch of these things and read one chunk from each,
then decode and send it on up the line.

It even works with the download-resumption logic; any
buffered-but-not-yielded bytes are thrown away, so we don't have to
worry about Frankenfragments getting into the decoder.

Change-Id: Iec69ded49d1735a793c6a82984146903100ee443
"}]
commit_message:
Make GetOrHeadHandler take an optional chunk size.

If given the chunk size, chunks are yielded to the client in exactly
that size (except the last chunk). Data read from the object server
will be buffered until there's a full chunk.

This is good for EC because we can set this to the size of a fragment,
then instantiate a bunch of these things and read one chunk from each,
then decode and send it on up the line.

It even works with the download-resumption logic; any
buffered-but-not-yielded bytes are thrown away, so we don't have to
worry about Frankenfragments getting into the decoder.

Change-Id: Iec69ded49d1735a793c6a82984146903100ee443

reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 7, 'name': 'Jay Pipes', 'email': 'jaypipes@gmail.com', 'username': 'jaypipes'}, {'_account_id': 1653, 'name': 'garyk', 'email': 'gkotton@vmware.com', 'username': 'garyk'}, {'_account_id': 1779, 'name': 'Daniel Berrange', 'email': 'berrange@redhat.com', 'username': 'berrange'}, {'_account_id': 2271, 'name': 'Michael Still', 'email': 'mikal@stillhq.com', 'username': 'mikalstill'}, {'_account_id': 2750, 'name': 'Sean Dague', 'email': 'sean@dague.net', 'username': 'sdague'}, {'_account_id': 5170, 'name': 'Microsoft Hyper-V CI', 'email': 'hyper-v_ci@microsoft.com', 'username': 'hyper-v-ci', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 5511, 'name': 'Nikola Dipanov', 'email': 'ndipanov@redhat.com', 'username': 'ndipanov'}, {'_account_id': 7730, 'name': 'Sahid Orentino Ferdjaoui', 'email': 'sahid.ferdjaoui@industrialdiscipline.com', 'username': 'sahid'}, {'_account_id': 9008, 'name': 'VMware NSX CI', 'username': 'vmwareminesweeper', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 9420, 'name': 'Matthew Gilliard', 'email': 'matthew.gilliard@hp.com', 'username': 'gilliard'}, {'_account_id': 9578, 'name': 'DB Datasets CI', 'email': 'turbo-hipster@lists.rcbops.com', 'username': 'turbo-hipster', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 10118, 'name': 'IBM PowerKVM CI', 'email': 'kvmpower@linux.vnet.ibm.com', 'username': 'powerkvm', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 10385, 'name': 'Citrix XenServer CI', 'username': 'citrix_xenserver_ci', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 11103, 'name': 'Intel PCI CI', 'email': 'otc_cloud@163.com', 'username': 'intelotccloud', 'inactive': True, 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 12299, 'name': 'Paweł Koniszewski', 'email': 'pawel.koniszewski@gmail.com', 'username': 'pawel.koniszewski'}]
revisions:
[{'number': 8, 'created': '2015-02-18 14:31:13.000000000', 'files': ['nova/tests/unit/virt/libvirt/test_host.py', 'nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py', 'nova/virt/libvirt/host.py', 'nova/tests/unit/virt/libvirt/fakelibvirt.py', 'nova/tests/unit/virt/libvirt/test_driver.py'], 'message': 'libvirt: proper monitoring of live migration progress

The current live migration code simply invokes migrateToURI
and waits for it to finish, or raise an exception. It considers
all exceptions to mean the live migration aborted and the VM is
still running on the source host. This is totally bogus, as there
are a number of reasons why an error could be raised from the
migrateToURI call. There are at least 5 different scenarios for
what the VM might be doing on source + dest host upon error.
The migration might even still be going on, even if after the
error has occurred.

A more reliable way to deal with this is to actively query
libvirt for the domain job status. This gives an indication
of whether the job is completed, failed or cancelled. Even
with that though, there is a need for a few heuristics to
distinguish some of the possible error scenarios.

This change to do active monitoring of the live migration process
also opens the door for being able to tune live migration on the
fly to adjust max downtime or bandwidth to improve chances of
getting convergence, or to automatically abort it after too much
time has elapsed instead of letting it carry on until the end of
the universe. This change merely records memory transfer progress
and leaves tuning improvements to a later date.

Closes-bug: #1414065
Change-Id: I6fcbfa31a79c7808c861bb3a84b56bd096882004
'}]
commit_message:
libvirt: proper monitoring of live migration progress

The current live migration code simply invokes migrateToURI
and waits for it to finish, or raise an exception. It considers
all exceptions to mean the live migration aborted and the VM is
still running on the source host. This is totally bogus, as there
are a number of reasons why an error could be raised from the
migrateToURI call. There are at least 5 different scenarios for
what the VM might be doing on source + dest host upon error.
The migration might even still be going on, even if after the
error has occurred.

A more reliable way to deal with this is to actively query
libvirt for the domain job status. This gives an indication
of whether the job is completed, failed or cancelled. Even
with that though, there is a need for a few heuristics to
distinguish some of the possible error scenarios.

This change to do active monitoring of the live migration process
also opens the door for being able to tune live migration on the
fly to adjust max downtime or bandwidth to improve chances of
getting convergence, or to automatically abort it after too much
time has elapsed instead of letting it carry on until the end of
the universe. This change merely records memory transfer progress
and leaves tuning improvements to a later date.

Closes-bug: #1414065
Change-Id: I6fcbfa31a79c7808c861bb3a84b56bd096882004

commit_message:
Unify usage of passwords and tokens

* secrete_token --> secret_token
* secret(e) --> secretsecret
* all passwords != secretsecret --> secretsecret
* all tokens != secret_token --> secret_token

Change-Id: I792fecff0c885bc14cda313ff15ea213adc49432
Partial-Bug: #1372639

commit_message:
gate devstack on gate-trove-functional-dsvm-mysql

Last night a change was made to devstack that caused Ironic, Trove,
and Trove-integration gates to fail.
This change proposes that we add the trove functional test to the
devstack gate, in order to prevent this from happening again.

The change from yesterday (2/11): https://review.openstack.org/#/c/154391/
The change that was applied to Trove to address the failure:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/155151

Change-Id: If0e1b52a9bfcb301877f5b2f6e80b2233b6872fa

subject: Log a warning when deprecated opts are used
revisions:
[{'number': 8, 'created': '2015-02-18 21:11:30.000000000', 'files': ['oslo_config/tests/test_cfg.py', 'oslo_config/cfg.py'], 'message': "Log a warning when deprecated opts are used

This change logs the warning at lookup time instead of parse time
because we have no way of knowing at parse time which options are
deprecated.  It does use a set to make sure it only logs a given
deprecation warning once per option so it won't spam the logs.

I could not find a way to log deprecations for cli args.  argparse
seems to only write the value to the undeprecated name, so there's
no way to tell whether it came from a deprecated name originally.
Since most of our opts are set through config files I don't see
this as a huge issue though.

I'm also not using the warnings module because its deprecation
mechanisms seem more developer focused, and for config opts we
need to notify the user.  This is not possible with the warnings
module in Python 2.6 (there's no way to send warnings to the log
by default), and since we still need to support that for oslo libs
I went with a simple logged warning instead.

Change-Id: I4580831f34c48882fb07288fa8d55272b58e2674
Closes-Bug: 1390408
"}]
commit_message:
Log a warning when deprecated opts are used

This change logs the warning at lookup time instead of parse time
because we have no way of knowing at parse time which options are
deprecated.  It does use a set to make sure it only logs a given
deprecation warning once per option so it won't spam the logs.

I could not find a way to log deprecations for cli args.  argparse
seems to only write the value to the undeprecated name, so there's
no way to tell whether it came from a deprecated name originally.
Since most of our opts are set through config files I don't see
this as a huge issue though.

I'm also not using the warnings module because its deprecation
mechanisms seem more developer focused, and for config opts we
need to notify the user.  This is not possible with the warnings
module in Python 2.6 (there's no way to send warnings to the log
by default), and since we still need to support that for oslo libs
I went with a simple logged warning instead.

Change-Id: I4580831f34c48882fb07288fa8d55272b58e2674
Closes-Bug: 1390408

commit_message:
Avoid httpretty 0.8.7 release

The 0.8.7 release of httpretty, which came out 2015-02-21, is causing
our test suite to enter an infinite loop on py34 runs. The issue appears
to be related to https://github.com/gabrielfalcao/HTTPretty/issues/221
which is biting others, with an unapplied but potential fix available at
https://github.com/gabrielfalcao/HTTPretty/pull/193.

Change-Id: Ifbc4b96fcd7293d5e7bb219f9ac51a9e91260b1d
Closes-Bug: 1424440

commit_message:
Catch PodNotFound during pod_delete and continue

Previous code wouldn't have completely fixed bug #1412587 as the
pod_delete from the conductor never caught the PodNotFound
exception. This slipped through the tests as the test,
'test_pod_delete_succeeds_when_not_found', was not set up properly.

This code fixes the test and implements a full fix.

Change-Id: I54cfc9f657179a63adb28a6986e528a74a6eeff6
Closes-bug: #1424473

commit_message:
Make bay-create fail when no argument passed.

Magnum command bay-create should fail when no
command line option is passed. This patch makes
baymodel_id parameter mandatory for creating bay.
